(his first home. We lived frugally, and our parents taught us the value of spending wisely.) Tj
T*
(Today's man-children, at the ripe old age of 40, still cannot afford a home. Yet they have no) Tj
T*
(problem eating out every day, going to the movies, and buying popcorn and avocado toast. Add in) Tj
T*
(subscriptions to ten different services they barely use, and that's money thrown out the) Tj
T*
(window. They don't see the correlation between their spending habits and their inability to buy) Tj
T*
(a home or save money in the first place. I understand that my grandfather's house only cost) Tj
T*
($12,000, and my father bought his for $50,000. Mine was much more expensive, I paid $150,000,) Tj
T*
(and that house is now worth a million. I understand that by the time my children are 26, it) Tj
T*
(will probably be worth $10 million. If they start saving now, they'll have a shot. But I can) Tj
T*
(tell they will choose reckless spending over saving, and I simply do not unde...) Tj
