(7. Go interfaces, reflection, and binary size) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-06-28T02:17:32Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/programming/GoInterfacesReflectAndBinarySize) Tj
T*
(Recently an interesting series of commits landed in Prometheus with the goal of reducing the) Tj
T*
(size of the Prometheus binary by allowing the Go linker to remove more unused code \( something) Tj
T*
(it's quite good at in general , although the linker is also deliberately limited in this \). The) Tj
T*
(commit with the message that's most informative about what is going on and why is) Tj
T*
(discovery/gce: keep [Google Cloud] Compute SD client from defeating dead-code elimination , and) Tj
T*
(you can read the full details in it. The short version is that if you're using certain sorts of) Tj
T*
(reflection anywhere in your program, the Go linker won't remove exported \(public\) methods of) Tj
T*
(any concrete type that's reachable through an interface. It doesn't matter how narrow the) Tj
T*
(interface is \(it can be the famous and minimal fmt.Stringer \); the moment you combine) Tj
T*
(reflection and a concrete type in an interface, the Go linker more or less stops throwing out) Tj
T*
(unused functions and methods. Well, sort of, as the commit explains. Unlike the standard Go) Tj
T*
(toolchain not doing dead code elimination for package level variables with constant values ,) Tj
