(8. Examining circuit boards from the Space Shuttle's I/O Processor) Tj
T*
(Source: Ken Shirriff's blog | Published: 2026-06-28T09:11:20.022-07:00) Tj
T*
(Link: http://www.righto.com/2026/06/space-shuttle-io-processor-boards.html) Tj
T*
(The Space Shuttle's five 1 general-purpose computers played a critical role in each flight:) Tj
T*
(controlling the engines, monitoring thousands of sensors, displaying data to the astronauts,) Tj
T*
(and navigating the Shuttle. Each computer consisted of two 60-pound aluminum-alloy boxes: the) Tj
T*
(box on the right is the CPU, a 32-bit processor that executed 420,000 instructions per second.) Tj
T*
(These computers were designed before microprocessors became popular, so the processor was built) Tj
T*
(from multiple boards crammed with simple chips and they used magnetic core memory rather than) Tj
T*
(DRAM chips. The Space Shuttle IOP and CPU \(AP-101B\). Photo courtesy of RR Auction . The box on) Tj
T*
(the left is the I/O Processor \(IOP\): the link between the CPU and the rest of the Shuttle. It) Tj
T*
(implemented the input/output capabilities for the computer, primarily 24 high-speed networks) Tj
T*
(that connected the computer to the Shuttle's systems and sensors. But the IOP wasn't just a) Tj
T*
(peripheral; it was a separate programmable computer, more complicated than the main CPU. The) Tj
T*
(IOP had an unusual architecture: it was one of the first multi-threaded computers, implementing) Tj
T*
(25 virtual processors \(with two completely different instruction sets\) t...) Tj
T*
